i will be writing more about this soon.w

text:
the lyrics said, "help me mama'... over and over, they kept repeating, hitting me like a hammer. she was never there... my cries were heard, but never answered. there was always a reason she couldn't help.
as i wrapped christmas presents, avoiding all the christmas music and cheer, those lryics played. i don't even have christmas day memories with my mom. she'll be there tomorrow for my baby sister and my niece, but she's never been there for me or for my children.
for just a little bit, i'm allowing myself to mourn the mother i never had.

text:
before donning her seasonal hat, my 16 year old dog could not help but reflect on the past year. like many, she pondered what direction we are headed, both as a country, and as a species (in this instance, she mostly thought of the human kind). with so many who have lost so much in 2018, we choose to decidedly focus on what we are grateful for. out of #metoo grew a timely invigorated consideration for women at all levels, but especially in leadership; while extreme views are still prevalent, their momentum is showing cracks; and the dire report on the state of the planet is making denialist seem even more out of step with reason while technology is paving a road of coming solutions. like my little bitch, we choose the bottle half full with a renewed faith in the power of conviction and the force of good. so tonight we celebrate in gratitude for all that we have. tomorrow we fight for reason, moderation, empathy and compassion. happy holidays my friends!

â€¢

oscar-winning actor #kevinspacey has been charged in connection with an allegation that he sexually abused an 18-year-old boy at a #nantucket, #massachusetts, bar more than two years ago, the local district attorney said on monday.

spacey is scheduled to be arraigned at nantucket district court on jan. 7 on a single charge of indecent assault and battery on a person who is at least 14 years old, according to court documents and a statement issued by cape and islands district attorney michael oâ€™keefe.

an attorney for spacey did not immediately reply to a request for comment. the actor, however, released a video on youtube on monday in which he adopts the persona of his character #frankunderwood in the popular netflix tv series â€œ#houseofcardsâ€ and says, â€œi know what you want, you want me back ... you wouldnâ€™t rush to judgments without facts, would you?â€ the 3-minute video makes no specific reference to the massachusetts allegation.

the charge against spacey, 59, whose full name is kevin spacey fowler, was filed after a dec. 20 hearing, oâ€™keefe said. the name on the complaint was kevin s. fowler.

the charge against spacey follows an allegation in november 2017 by boston television journalist heather unruh that her 18-year-old son was sexually assaulted by the actor at the club car restaurant and bar in nantucket on july 7, 2016.

at a news conference in which she made the allegations, unruh said her â€œstar struckâ€ son falsely told the actor he was old enough to drink when he met him at the bar. the legal age to drink alcoholic beverages in massachusetts is 21. â€œkevin spacey bought him drink after drink after drink, and when my son was drunk, spacey made his move and sexually assaulted him,â€ unruh said at the 2017 news conference.

the actor allegedly stuck his hands into her sonâ€™s pants and grabbed his genitals, she said, adding it was â€œcompletely unexpectedâ€ and her son tried unsuccessfully to shift his body away from spacey. ğŸ–ğŸ¾more in commentsğŸ‘‡ğŸ¾

.
.

three years ago i was raped and the guy who did it is now a cop. the ptsd symptoms have been in full force. so to all the people who've been *offended* by anything i've said or done in the last week or so, this is why. so kindly, fuck off. .
.

i am only sharing in case it can help someone but mostly bc i am losing my gd mind. i still believe everything happens for a reason & growth will come from this. .
soo thank u, merry freakin' christmas & goodnight. .
. ..
.

text:
pink (2016) | hindi | aniruddha roy chowdhury
.
i was so grateful for this movie when it came out - finally a movie that explained the meaning of consent in the best way possible. growing up in the 90s, many of us have seen films and song sequences where the usual accepted way to woo a girl was to stalk her, sing and dance around her until she 'falls in love' with the male lead. i saw the 1999 movie aarzoo where akshay kumar forcefully kisses madhuri dixit to get back at her for some small accident on the road. and voilÃ , she is lovestruck ! (after few moments of reluctance at least.) i am glad we have come a long way since then and learnt to speak against this kind of movie sequences, and also giving importance to the #metoo movement. and this should apply to both genders. the consent of men is as important as that of women.
.
merry christmas everyone !
.
.
.
.

text:
us actor kevin spacey has been charged with sexually assaulting a teenager at a bar in massachusetts. he will appear in court on 7 january over the incident, which allegedly occurred in nantucket in july 2016. on monday, mr spacey posted a video in which he appears to deny any wrongdoing while in character as frank underwood from house of cards. "i'm certainly not going to pay the price for the things i didn't do," he says in the clip. "you wouldn't believe the worst without evidence, would you?" he asks. "you wouldn't rush to judgements without facts." mr spacey delivers the statement in frank underwood's accentÂ and addresses the viewer directly, much like his character did throughout his five seasons on house of cards. the three-minute clip marks his first public appearance since the first allegation of sexual assault was made against him in november 2017. he was accused by actor anthony rapp of making a sexual advance in 1986 and a number of other allegations have since emerged. mr spacey claimed to have no memory of the events but publicly apologised before issuing an "absolute" denial of the other allegations. in september,Â the los angeles county district attorney's office said mr spacey would not be prosecutedÂ over a separate accusation of sexual assault that allegedly took place in 1992. it said it fell outside california's statute of limitations. the controversy has led to the actor being axed from a number of roles, including from house of cards and the 2017 film all the money in the world, which was re-shot without him. a film in which he appears, billionaire boys club, also took a record-breaking low of $126 on its first night in us cinemas in august.
#metoo
#metoocampaign
#hollywoodsexualharassmentscandal #kevinspacey #newsoftheday #breakthenews

text:
ğŸ„#tbt a diamond bracelet for christmas that comes with a priceğŸ„
-
-âœ¨ this was the christmas after my ex got me the mercedes 500 sl. the one i shared a couple of posts back. he felt he had to match that gift.
-
-âœ¨hence i ended up with a $120,000 diamind bracelet. too bad things like that don't bring happiness. excitement but not happiness. i really thought back then i had everything a girl could want. little did i know that came with a huge price.
-
-âœ¨ i do remember back then feeling like it was so important we had an equal relationship. i didn't want to just take. i wanted to give back to him the way he was giving to me. i truly loved this man so going out of my way to make him feel special was easy.
-
-âœ¨ i had my high powered corporate career so i had money. but of course i didn't spend $120,000 on him.
-
-âœ¨i spent forever looking for the perfect gift. finally i got him a one of kind antique watch. to make it special on an emotional level i had it engraved on the back. it said i will always love you. boy did he take advantage of that engraved promise.
-
-âœ¨when he wanted me back i remember meeting him for dinner and sure enough he walked in wearing that watch. it didn't work. but that didn't stop him. he felt he had to go to any lengths to get me back. even if that meant destroying my life.
-

text:
itâ€™s so disheartening when the people who should be cheering for  you the loudest, remain silent. .

these are days where we need all the strength and courage we can get to run our race and finish our course. .

we have no time to waste or emotional bandwidth to spare,  trying to convince those who should be for us to act as if they are. .

donâ€™t try and carry those who want to pull you down. .

donâ€™t waste time trying to convince others of your worth and value. .

donâ€™t expend valuable energy minimizing you so that others feel more comfortable around you. .

a smaller you does not make a bigger them. 
donâ€™t try to hang on to those who have let go of you. .

donâ€™t be controlled by those who wonâ€™t allow you to thrive and flourish. .

make sure those closes to you are for you, talk to you not about you, are not jealous of you, not threatened by you, not intimidated by you, not wanting to leverage you, and donâ€™t want to be you. .

you need them to be them and to bring out the best in you. .

those closest to you are the ones that truly have the capacity to hurt you or heal you. .

choose your circle wisely.

text:
dear person in ministry,

will you stop seeking your own success, your own fame, your own superiority, your own prominence, your own church growth, your own net worth, and will you just go out and love someone? can you stop it with you? can you sacrifice everything that has to do with you to just go and love others more than yourself? this is your highest calling. not your church title of pastor, teacher, prophet, etc. not your spiritual gifts. not your ministry plans. your love. expressed. given. shared. poured out.

as it is right now, many of you are like the disciples in john 13 who are competing to be the greatest.

merry christmas and a very happy new year to you all from us. hereâ€™s a quote that remains both inspiring and powerful from #nelsonmandela used for our show by curator @rosalindnldavis to frame the show and his #obituary painted by @hughmendes11 and a range of artists in the show who have painted #rulebreakers and #pioneers and the truth... in order of appearance after hugh is 
1.
@thedavincitobe who painted eliza orme the first female allowed to the bar 100 years ago.
2. @peterkennardx #photomontage created in protest to the uk and britainâ€™s invasion of iraq. 
3. @juanbolivarstudio2112 piece referring to breaking through the bars of persecution.
4. @kazzdouieart breaking through #mentalhealth barriers and shining a light through her work.
5. @vanessamitter brides who resonate in a #metoo movement energy in the defiant expressions of women who will not be dismissed.
6. @march.alex #feminist questionings 
7. @justinjhibbs depiction of the pioneering #jazzmusician #nathandavis who not only had a major impact on jazz in the 60â€™s but also pioneered #africanamericanmusic in #universities in the us.
8. @mrdavidlock who not only celebrates the #burghersofcalais but also male desire and the civil liberties and #gayrights that is possible after many years of persecution struggle, passion and hope. 
a huge thanks to all the artists who have exhibited with us over the year and all you beautiful people who have visited the shows and been part of them over the years. we will continue detailing the shows of 2018  and the many artists we have exhibited during the year and more . thanks to the team at collyer bristow for all their support with ğŸ’š curator @rosalindnldavis ğŸ™ #seeyouinthenewyear #rulesoffreedom #cbgartists #holborngallery #galleryinalawfirm #supportingartists

summary:
â€œin this poignant memoir of personal transformation, jill soloway takes us on a patriarchy-toppling emotional and professional journey. when jillâ€™s parent came out as transgender, jill pushed through the male-dominated landscape of hollywood to create the groundbreaking and award-winning amazon tv series transparent. exploring identity, love, sexuality, and the blurring of boundaries through the dynamics of a complicated and profoundly resonant american family, transparent gave birth to a new cultural consciousness. while working on the show and exploding mainstream ideas about gender, jill began to erase the lines on their own map, finding their voice as a director, show creator, and activist.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
she wants it: desire, power, and toppling the patriarchy moves with urgent rhythms, wild candor, and razor-edged humor to chart jillâ€™s evolution from straight, married mother of two to identifying as queer and nonbinary. this intense and revelatory metamorphosis challenges the status quo and reflects the shifting power dynamics that continue to shape our collective worldview. with unbridled insight that offers a rare front seat to the inner workings of the #metoo movement and its aftermath, jill captures the zeitgeist of a generation with thoughtful and revolutionary ideas about gender, inclusion, desire, and consent.â€
ğŸ“–

text:
what do you think of this pic?

i was assaulted sexually when this pic was taken.
let me confess this story. 
before i joined the dance company, i took many dance auditions and once there was a photographer during the audition. he was like 50s and asked me to photoshoot sometime after the audition. as dancers getting the offer to the photoshoot is always good deal. he even sent me the pic taken during the audition and told me he has enough space to photoshoot,so the place was at his place. 
i didn't have any fear to go there because he "looked" a pro photographer. actually the photoshoot was great as you see the pic but it was till we had a break. 
somehow i told i had a back pain and he told that he gave me massage. it is my fault. 
i actually didn't know what was the border, but he definitely touched my boobs. 
i was like...it could be a part of the  massage ....at the same time i really really got scared and when he almost tried to touch down there, i finally could say please don't. that was the most disgusting thing ever. 
he made the stupid excuses and the rest of the photoshoot was really awkward. 
after that he gave me only a few pics even he took many pics of mine,which also makes me feel mad.  it was too scared to tell this story till now.
since it happened, i sometimes reject the offer to the photoshoot.i feel like i lose the good photoshoot opportunities tho.

we have to know there are people who do not have any respect like him. we can't be always gullible like me. i'm not good at saying no telling people my negativity. i am scared to see guys and at the same time i don't  expect anything from them and get sarcastic because of it. that would be why i always smile, so honestly i'm scared if i can't say no and the same thing might happen.... i want to overcome this traumatic experience. i want to challenge everything and join as many projects as i can.

i just don't want to keep this traumatic experience in my mind anymore,so i confessed. 
hope you read this and know just posting the picture is not always showing how happy i am in the life. showing the weakness is showing the reality

text:
magnetic deflection of a tv image

an cathode ray tube (crt) television is connected to a video camera. when a strong magnet is brought close to the television screen, the image becomes warped and discolored. while many new televisions use flat screen technology, older crts produced images by firing electron guns (one red, one green, one blue) through the television body onto the back of the screen. when a magnet is brought close to the screen, it deflects the paths of the electron beams and distorts the picture. a strong enough magnetic field can even create a hole in the electron beams, causing a black spot on the picture. this tv has been subject to many magnet encounters, which has permanently damaged the picture. 
cr_mit_research

you guys! do your future self a favor and take some time to reflect on your dreams this holiday season. they are inside of you for a reason. pursue them! i share this story with you to say that with strategy and calculated risk, you can achieve those dreams. this one all started when we visited gatlinburg for christmas 3 years ago and called a realtor after falling in love with the cabin vibe and idea of having a holiday gathering for generations to come. we craved tradition and this just felt right, especially knowing that the side stream of income from my skincare business would cover the mortgage. then we decided to make a vacation rental out of it to future diversify our income with hopes of major time freedom.

today, we stand here in awe of what became possible and hope that you will be encouraged by us; two regular people that just dared to dream. who knows?! maybe skincare will be the vehicle to take you there too? gift yourself a business this year and letâ€™s get dreaming! iâ€™ll show you the way. ğŸ‘¯â€â™€ï¸

text:
i had to lay down my pride and ask for help in order to move forward.
.
there, i said it. i was on the struggle bus to struggle town after having my first daughter. i was so sleep-deprived, battling a bad latch/lip-tie/thrush, colic so bad i had to hold her all.the.time (so much i had to receive a cortisone shot in my wrist and wear a brace because of holding her so much).
.
i get up enough gumption to begin exercising again and bam. i was served a slice of humble pie when i realized my body was not even close to capable of handling what i was throwing at it. and i was discouraged. i hated running and the gym wasnâ€™t an option.
.
what did i do? naturally i reached out for help from a stranger on the internetğŸ˜œwho was also a mom and was offering another way. she was kind, informative and followed through. what she did is open a door to show me what i could do.
.
what if i had stuck my nose up and been too stubborn to reach out for help? iâ€™d probably still be be-bopping around on the internet trying and failing different random workouts and difficult to commit to diets.
.
you might be the girl on the left right now but i want you to be the girl on the right (now post 2 babies & a miscarriage) who reaches out for help from a stranger on the internet and can say, 4 years from now, â€œiâ€™m glad i said yes!â€
.
thereâ€™s a spot for you in my next group and i want you with me and my girls crushing 2019! youâ€™re not going to want to miss prep week and day 1 on january 14! show me your most used emoji (ğŸ‘ğŸ» is mine!) and weâ€™ll have you rolling in no time!

text:
i don't know how well i can explain this painting right now, because i was in a completely different mindset when i did this. 
also, i'm not so good with words. exactly the reason why i express through paints. 
still, i'll try. 
okay, so sometimes we feel things that don't exist anywhere other than that one dark corner of our minds. and we feel them so so hard, that we lose ourselves; become a void, or worse, our existence starts feeling negative. 
we rub out every inch of assurance our mind gives us about our positive side. 
it's as if we bully ourselves. and become victims. also, self is the worst enemy one could have. because in that case, we know every weak point of ours and exploit it recklessly. what i've painted here is the physical representation of the above.

on today we lift you up. we stand with you in the face of injustice. injustice against you and other black and brown bodies. we speak truth and stare patriarchy and racism in the  eyes. the problem here extends beyond the law. it brings up the ugly truth that the bodies of women, especially those that are black and brown are seen as inherently invaluable and especially when compared to the value of a white man. cyntoia brown a student, a visionary, a change maker, a survivor. we believe you. we believe you and others who have been forced by violence, coercion and fear tactics into dangerous situations only to be villanized later. her story sounds painfully familiar and that is why we connect so deeply. we have been victims of abuse and told that we liked it, asked for it or deserved it in some way. we have been called liars. we have been punished for telling our truth and thrown in jail for protecting ourselves. in spite of those things, we still find our light and muster up the strength to help others. we use our experience and stories as tools for the liberation of future generations. this is the magic they speak of. it is conjured from pain, tears and blood. we will persevere!!! no matter what!
#cyntoiabrown #metoo

text:
hello! this is grimm! i started streaming earlier this year but stopped due to issues at home and physical insecurities about showing my face online. 
some of the first few viewers who saw how i looked when i streamed made me feel uncomfortable.

as a woman of color with bigger features such as chest and glutes, i got positive comments saying "you're beautiful and funny" but also "you're thicc" or "let me hit that you chocolate goddess"...gross.. i already get sexually harassed enough by cat callers but i refuse to deal with that bs online as well. 
i know "b**bie streamers" and some other females out there tend to flaunt their assets for views but i refuse to partake in that. 
this will be my facecam for the time being.

i made this yesterday morning to "mock" those females who purposely abuse their looks to their advantage. 
it's hard trying to get recognition in a community predominately male but going the full "exposing your physical body for views" is not the way to go. your personality defines you. not your body.

text:
dear silence,

i wonder, how chaotic my life would have been without you! too obvious, huh?

since childhood, you've always been my best friend, my chaperone and at tough times, my everything. be it the wrath of exams or the trembles of result noons, the quest of ways for skipping punishments or the hunt for daunting ice-breakers in order to start a conversation, you've always swayed your comforting palms on me. 
there have been times when my heart ached and i wished to tear it apart, in order to to free myself from all the whereabouts of this gloomy life. dreams, fantasies, crushes, love, breakups...damn, it'd be a never ending list. you've seen me at every up and down. you're the friend who knows my darkest secret, whom i could talk to without bothering my larynx and most importantly, who'd agree to every shit i utter. you're the diary which never existed.

i've had many friends, many left, some are still there who claim to be by my side through every thick and thin but i know that we're going to have our differences and some day we'll part. but you my friend, you are the sheath that holds our stars and you'll stick with me till eternity.

hoping to meet you at the other end of universe,

until then,
a somebody.

sourav dey.
(@quill_and_paper)
.
.
.

most of us are taught from a very early age that anger is a â€˜badâ€™ emotion. where are told to manage it, to keep it in check. and so, most of us learn to ignore itâ€”to shove our angry feelings deep, deep down where they wonâ€™t upset anyone. butÂ censoringÂ your anger isnâ€™t healthy. in fact,Â finding a way to improve your relationship withÂ anger can be tremendouslyÂ beneficial.

first off, it is important to remember that there are no â€˜badâ€™ emotions. each of your feelingsÂ is a valid form of experience. they are all completely human, and none of them are innately â€˜badâ€™. itâ€™s how you handle and express those feelings that truly matters.

with anger, many of us tend to lose our coolâ€”scream, stomp, punch, fume. thatâ€™s destructive anger. but if you redefine your relationship to anger, expressing it can actually be an incredibly positive experienceâ€”meaning your anger can actually be productive.

1. anger can promote personal growth.

think of anger as a force for positive change in your life. it can provide insights to our deepest valuesâ€¦ as well as our deepest faults. by becoming aware of these parts of yourself and expressing them in a healthy way, you can actually grow and evolve as a person.

sure, there is a lot of discomfort in experiencing and acknowledging angerâ€”but youâ€™ll come out the other side a wiser, better version of yourself.
2. it kicks you into gear.
without anger, you might not ever take action to address the things that truly upset you. anger is a very clear sign that you are not happy with something in life, and it can provide the fire you need to roll your sleeves up and do something about it.

according to anger-management expertjohn schinnerer, phd, â€œbeing mad can be good for society; it motivates us to work toward positive change. things like #metoo or the civil rights movement wouldnâ€™t exist without anger.â€
3. it reminds you what is important to you.

text:
i wanted to share this exhibition essay i wrote for cave drawings, man - the solo show of new drawings by @golden_suz suzanne goldenberg @the_provincial - these drawings are poignant and relevant in so many ways. up one more week - please message to make an appointment. .suzanne goldenberg is a ny based artist, writer, and activist. she works with a vast variety of media including drawing, collage, textiles, video and sculpture, and currently hosts the crush poetry series at woodbine in ridgewood, ny. 
emerging from a conversation between the artist and a good friend, the title cave drawings, man refers to getting to the essence of drawing and materials. â€œi mean they didnâ€™t build the cave to do the drawing on it, just picked whatever wall they could find and started communicating,â€ suzanne texted.

this new series of work signals a feverish return to drawing after a 10 year interval. stoked by motion picture influences, the drawings are made with uniball micropoint pens and markers on castoff manilla folders and binder tabs. figural images, caught in flash moments of doom, terror or grief, are sourced from classic french cinema, fassbinder movies, and clips perhaps burned in her brain from studying film at mcgill university. 
it also marks a shift from suzanneâ€™s last solo show at gallery molly krom of large, wall-mounted and loom-like unfurling textiles, along with her minimal, delicate and precarious wire sculptures, which have been instrumental to her practice for years. in her previous sculptural works suzanne positioned the question of making and unmaking at its core, suggesting a breakdown and failure of productive systems. here, in cave drawings, man, as in the political moment we find ourselves, a feeling pervades that we are still in the dark, and in dark times. 
the sight of perilous gestures of mostly women, drawn loosely from film clips, has a way of feeding uneasy questions just a year into harvey weinstein and the film industry answering to the #metoo movement, finally beginning  to account for years of fostering a culture of sexual assault and abuse. how do we reconcile these gestures that keep recurring? how do we look at a once assumed ...

text:
"almost everything written about childhood emotional wounds talks about the pain of not receiving the love we craved. but no one ever mentions the devastating pain of not being able to give the love we longed to give. our desire to give love is just as great as our desire to receive it, and we have a natural craving to feel that our love for others matters. we want to see that our love can inspire, that it can energize, that it can heal. there is no music more delightful than hearing someone say to us, 'my life has really changed for the better since you came into it.' if youâ€™re frustrated that people in your life are not accepting the transformative power of your love, that doesn't mean that you're "co-dependent"; more likely you're just in need of people who are willing and able to receive.
 one of the early steps toward healing is to explore our memories, from childhood and adulthood, of longing to give. the world's failure to recognize, accept, and value our love plays a central role in how we've all ended up so wounded." ----- from the joyous recovery: a new path to emotional healing and freedom by lundy bancroft, forthcoming march 2019 #lundybancroft

text:
a few months later, in autumn 2013, wylie met steve bannon. at the time, he was editor-in-chief of breitbart, which he had brought to britain to support his friend nigel farage in his mission to take britain out of the european union.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. heâ€™s the only straight man iâ€™ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

carole cadwalladr

this is something i personally am working on for 2019. most of my life i've heard everything from you can't do this, look at others doing better than you, you can never do anything right or good, etc i hear it from someone that is suppose to a parent, my supporter but instead it's the opposite always poking away at my self esteem i took it and believed the lie for a really long time, i have depression and anxiety. however i'm stronger then i gave myself credit for because i was a positive person to those who came across me because i wasn't expose to that. so my dear residents you are not alone, and he/she does not know what's in your heart. make plans to support yourself no matter how small

text:
with christmas and 2018's last week just around the corner, 
eyp slovenia would like to take a week to reflect on what we have achieved this year.

even though, european youth parliament is a gender equal organisation, we have decided that this year in light of #metoo movement, we take on the next week to embrace the main pillars of our organisation that are too many times forgotten - women of eyp slovenia.

oprah winfrey has opened the year of 2018 with the next words: "a new day is on the horizon, and when that new day finally dawns it will be because of a lot of magnificent women..." for the next seven days, we are going to look back on 2018 with statistics of this years eyp slovenia's database to remind all of us how incredible, inspiring and motivational female are.

day 1 of #aweekofeypsloveniaswomen:

this year, 6 out of 10 head organisers of our session were female. with a rate of 60%, we embrace and thank all the girls that stood up to the challenge of head organising a session and did not let anyone stop them at achieving their set goals.

thank you!

text:
"there are moments you think you know it all and bam one incident breaks the myth and puts you in front of the reality. #metoo was one such movement for me! here i was sitting comfortably thinking that equality has arrived seeing my female colleagues getting equal responsibility and pay for the same work but that isn't enough (if it's there).
the movement shook me hard and made me realise that we as men need to be more respectful towards women not only the ones we work with but who're around us. what i liked about it the most was that it put some accountability on men about their actions and in future they'll think twice before doing something this heinous. of course the film fraternity was in lime light but the effect it had could be felt everywhere around you. we need to credit women and laud them for coming out and telling their stories to the world which some are afraid to tell even their loved ones. hope it will make more men accountable and makes every environment a comfortable one for women in 2019!" - @tellmestories
#lovestruckby2018 #womenempowerment #safeworkingenvironment

#ecstaticyetchaoticrecommends
"swan song" by kelleigh greenberg-jephcott
â˜•
truman capote is known for his dazzling writing style. his most famous book 'in cold blood' is a nonfiction that is written in a true fiction style. but capote's life is a controversial one and here is a book that is loosely based on the capote's difficult childhood, his entry into the circles of the rich and famous, and his indulgence in gossip, followed by betrayal.
-
one fine day, truman capote, a respectable member of the new york elite, decides to publish a blog revealing the dirtiest and innermost secrets of each of the members, without a hint of remorse.
by his charming personality, capote was known to attract women who then had different roles in his life. some were his source of inspiration, while others were pure amusement.
-
swan song by kelleigh greenberg-jephcott bring us the bling of the elite society, the subsequent bomb that capote dropped and all this charting to his disturbing childhood. a work of fiction that has facts from capote's life and is then built into an indulging, thrilling story.

text:
â–º exhibition â–º ''will she ever shut up? by betty tompkins'' @bettytompkinsart at p.p.o.w gallery ( @ppowgallery ), new york. pictured, the artist's latest series 'apologia' fuses the #metoo movement with old master paintings in a comment on gender equality.

tompkins is a pioneering feminist artist, best known for her direct depiction of the female body, sexuality, and desire through paintings, drawings, photographs, and video works. the exhibition title comes from a phrase submitted as part of tompkins' original women words project, which tompkins worked on from 2002-2015, and serves as a poignant and humorous lens through which to grapple with the themes that tompkins explores in her current exhibition. the show features a new body of women words that tompkins has created using pages torn from photography and art history books. the works feature phrases that tompkins sourced from audience response cards from tompkins' exhibitions at flag art foundation ( @flagartfoundation )and gavlak gallery ( @gavlakgaller ). the responses yielded largely crude and sexual language about women. in these works, the text that tompkins gathered is painted over well-known works from art history, obscuring the female figures. created on paintings that span the renaissance to the mid-twentieth century, this series variously features work by brassÃ¤i, richard avedon, jan van eyck, weegee, bruce davidson, rembrandt, and vermeer. 
#awita #womaninthearts #womanartist #exhibition #bettytompkins #metoo #ppowgallery

beach finds ğŸ’« footsteps to inspire takes me to beaches off the beaten track or to places where we wouldn't even think about the beach. 16 kilometres is a long distance and sometimes i discover hidden gems or have unexpected experiences. in zanzibar last year i actually ran from one town to another...in a remote part of the world like this, each town is unique and has it's own soul. jambiani where i started is a working village, men fish and women grow algaes. paje, the town where i turned around is a little more touristy and well known for the good kite-surfing winds.â €

ğŸ“· this photo is from my recent run in vietnam at ho tram beach - about 150km from ho chi minh city. there is not much info in english about this beach because it's not on the tourist track. the beach goes for miles. i began my run in one direction but didn't feel a safe energy so turned around and headed in the national park direction. so amazing. lots of families on the beach enjoying the water and 9 kilometres down the beach i came across these boats. they are #fishermen bowls. first time seeing a round boat ğŸ¤” being afternoon, the fisherman were already chilling from their morning of work. i enjoyed the moment to take some photos and explore the boats. hihihi quite cool that this photo definitely tells us i'm in vietnam ğŸ‡»ğŸ‡³â €

text_retweet:
reposted from @mattmcgorry -  from @chenchenwrites . i echo this to anyone who is part of a privileged group that claims to be baffled but what to do and how to help. start reading. start googling. i keep hearing men proclaiming to be confused by how to date in the â€œ#metoo era.â€ if we committed to reading books and googling articles by women (and especially women of color) about feminism how to end rape culture, and sexual violence, we would find the answers we are looking for. we can follow and repost the voices of the marginalized on this very issues. but for all of this to happen, we first have to accept that there are things outside of our first-person experience that we donâ€™t have a full understanding of. and as white people, and/or men, we have to be willing to listen to and value the voices we are taught to devalue. if you only expect to learn from men and especially white men (consciously or not), we will never be able to learn about other peopleâ€™s lives, and in turn our own unexamined perspectives that we hold to be objective and unbiased. itâ€™s time to wake up.

#exposethetruth

text:
| balance | one of the things this recovery has taught me is finding balance. listening to my body and mind, knowing my boundaries and stretching them without crossing them. 
today i was tired after two visits to the physiotherapists and even though i really wanted to go to the gym i had to be strong and say no. no, not now, not today, tomorrow maybe. now is time for rest and taking it easy as i need this. so it is ok. 
how is your inner voice talking to you? (ps my dinner from last night was well balanced as you can tell!)
#brokennotbeaten #balance #recovery #innervoice #strength #daretosayno #glutenfree #pizzalover #pizza  @newyorkpizza_nl

one year ago today i decided that i owed my life to the person who raped me. i decided on this day last year, to try to take my own life because what he did to me made me feel like my life wasnâ€™t worth living. the pain i was living in everyday, with the constant depression, anxiety, ptsd, flashbacks, night terrors .. i decided that pain wasnâ€™t worth it. i would rather be at peace than have to live with the feelings and thoughts i was having everyday. iâ€™m trying to make this not so long because no one wants to read a book, but i just want anyone out there struggling to know that itâ€™s not worth it. suicide is not worth it. i promise. suicide is a permanent solution to a temporary problem that passes the pain you were feeling onto those you love. only difference is, your pain would have went away one day, theirs never will. iâ€™m sitting here today, one year later, telling you that it gets better. slowly, very slowly, but surely. #metoo #timesup #suicideawareness #thisisnotconsent
.

.
this quote by dr. elizabeth kubler-ross struck me deeply the first time i read it. i had never thought of myself as more loving, sensitive, compassionate, altruistic, and beautiful not in spite of, but because of â€” my painful experiences. .
.

.

.

beaware girls!!!
it can send shivers down your spine!
this is what you get in return when you fight for your self! 
this is india, incredible india i must say..
my sister being the victim of an extremely unpleasant touch by a stranger in the streets of chandni chowk.
in reward of catching him red handed and slapping him, i got a slap back on the left side of my face by the accused which lead to severe injury in the retina and after half and hour of calling delhi police, i got a call back from them asking "where are you ma'am?"
thanks to the market people for catching and beating him tight but unfortunately he managed to run away!
the only question that strikes my mind is-
did i deserve this injury?
.
.
#repost #beawaregirls #bestrong #thisisindia 
spread it as much as you can, this can happen to you too!
.
.

text:
i recently found this photo from this past summer and felt i needed to post this.

for anyone who thinks they're alone... you are not. i was brutally attacked by someone i barely knew. i made a terrible decision to go with them but they made an even worse decision to put their hands on my body. i had bruises all over the rest of my body as well but this is where they choked me. you can only see the three fingerprints and the bruise from his bite in the middle. on the other side there is a bruise from his thumb, as well. i'm terribly sorry to anyone who has experienced any abuse of any type and even more sorry to those who felt they couldn't report/were bullied out of it. keep your head up and your heart soft. there is love out there. love is kind and caring and will not ever lay a hand on you. #metoo #selfloveisthebestlove #wiccanbitch

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

a few months later, in autumn 2013, wylie met steve bannon. at the time, he was editor-in-chief of breitbart, which he had brought to britain to support his friend nigel farage in his mission to take britain out of the european union.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. heâ€™s the only straight man iâ€™ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
a few months later, in autumn 2013, wylie met steve bannon. at the time, he was editor-in-chief of breitbart, which he had brought to britain to support his friend nigel farage in his mission to take britain out of the european union.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. heâ€™s the only straight man iâ€™ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text_retweet:
beaware girls!!!
it can send shivers down your spine!
this is what you get in return when you fight for your self! 
this is india, incredible india i must say..
my sister being the victim of an extremely unpleasant touch by a stranger in the streets of chandni chowk.
in reward of catching him red handed and slapping him, i got a slap back on the left side of my face by the accused which lead to severe injury in the retina and after half and hour of calling delhi police, i got a call back from them asking "where are you ma'am?"
thanks to the market people for catching and beating him tight but unfortunately he managed to run away!
the only question that strikes my mind is-
did i deserve this injury?
.
.
#repost #beawaregirls #bestrong #thisisindia 
spread it as much as you can, this can happen to you too!
.
.
